1
00:00:02,268 --> 00:00:07,820
<i>Radiologist, contact 5317.</i>

2
00:00:08,760 --> 00:00:10,830
- Amber.
- No.

3
00:00:10,910 --> 00:00:13,300
- Why not?
- Amber's a stripper name.

4
00:00:13,840 --> 00:00:16,220
Find me one stripper
named Amber Hartig.

5
00:00:17,210 --> 00:00:18,463
Or not. Okay.

6
00:00:19,040 --> 00:00:22,160
Non-stripper names. Um, Desiree?

7
00:00:22,540 --> 00:00:23,920
Bambi? Kandy Kane?

8
00:00:24,660 --> 00:00:25,660
Max.

9
00:00:26,480 --> 00:00:27,480
Maxine.

10
00:00:28,360 --> 00:00:30,420
Max Hartig.
It's a cute name, isn't it?

11
00:00:30,930 --> 00:00:32,860
If you're a professional boxer, maybe.

12
00:00:34,266 --> 00:00:36,564
Can you believe we made
this little creature?

13
00:00:36,860 --> 00:00:38,015
I know. It's incredible.

14
00:00:38,240 --> 00:00:40,440
It's the most amazing
thing we've ever done.

15
00:00:42,040 --> 00:00:43,760
I almost ran the marathon
last year.

16
00:00:44,470 --> 00:00:47,219
If we're lucky, you won't inherit
your daddy's sense of humor.

17
00:00:47,220 --> 00:00:50,180
Hello. Say "hi" to Bear.

18
00:00:53,550 --> 00:00:55,800
She hasn't even eaten anything.
Why is she spitting up?

19
00:00:56,880 --> 00:00:59,610
Well, honey, we can't bug them again.

20
00:00:59,620 --> 00:01:00,820
Okay, okay.

21
00:01:04,290 --> 00:01:07,720
I'm sorry. It's our first kid. We're
both a little panicky, I guess.

22
00:01:07,730 --> 00:01:10,557
Well, you gotta ask the pediatrician
next time. I just deliver 'em.

23
00:01:11,500 --> 00:01:14,740
- Is she spitting up?
- Yeah. Second time in an hour.

24
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:17,730
Oh. If you lived underwater
for nine months,

25
00:01:18,220 --> 00:01:19,840
you'd have a lot to spit up too.

26
00:01:24,220 --> 00:01:27,115
- Is something wrong?
- A little lethargic.

27
00:01:27,560 --> 00:01:29,440
- Well, we didn't think...
- She's hot.

28
00:01:31,980 --> 00:01:32,980
Is she...

29
00:01:33,720 --> 00:01:35,590
The baby's seizing!
Get the crash cart!

30
00:01:35,590 --> 00:01:38,250
- What's wrong?
- Need some help in here!

31
00:01:38,330 --> 00:01:40,320
Oh, God. Is she all right?

32
00:01:40,720 --> 00:01:42,630
- I.V. Access?
- No. Ativan.

33
00:01:42,640 --> 00:01:43,640
What's going on?

34
00:02:22,500 --> 00:02:23,713
The M.R.I.'s back.

35
00:02:24,500 --> 00:02:27,300
And? It's what we expected.

36
00:02:28,140 --> 00:02:30,070
The accident caused
serious damage.

37
00:02:31,740 --> 00:02:33,420
It's amnesia.

38
00:02:37,680 --> 00:02:38,680
<i>I'm sorry.</i>

39
00:02:40,320 --> 00:02:41,340
<i>I just can't believe it.</i>

40
00:02:48,330 --> 00:02:49,840
Enjoying our lounge, House?

41
00:02:50,530 --> 00:02:54,035
Just came in to get milk for my
coffee, which you're out of.

42
00:02:54,035 --> 00:02:54,940
Flat or sparkling?

43
00:02:54,940 --> 00:02:56,204
- Sparkling.
- Splat.

44
00:02:58,020 --> 00:03:00,458
So, the Hartigs?

45
00:03:00,700 --> 00:03:02,168
Their baby gets a fever.

46
00:03:02,168 --> 00:03:04,070
What, don't tell me...
the kid had a seizure.

47
00:03:04,080 --> 00:03:07,620
Yep. The parents, of course, start freaking,
and I have to deal with that for an hour.

48
00:03:07,960 --> 00:03:10,590
Like it was your fault. She was
perfect when I delivered her.

49
00:03:10,590 --> 00:03:12,880
If you wanna blame
someone, blame the pediatrician.

50
00:03:13,180 --> 00:03:14,500
So, how is the kid now?

51
00:03:14,960 --> 00:03:18,060
Bowel obstruction. She's under observation.
She'll be fine.

52
00:03:18,500 --> 00:03:20,520
Pediatrician
will take all the credit.

53
00:03:28,680 --> 00:03:31,406
Exhibit A: Baby Girl Hartig.

54
00:03:31,960 --> 00:03:33,700
Term baby, 42 hours old.

55
00:03:34,580 --> 00:03:37,250
Went into seizures six hours ago,
brought into the intensive care...

56
00:03:37,260 --> 00:03:39,456
diagnosed with obstruction
of the small bowel.

57
00:03:40,150 --> 00:03:42,710
I'm still amazed you're actually
in the same room with a patient.

58
00:03:42,780 --> 00:03:44,770
People don't bug me
until they get teeth.

59
00:03:45,250 --> 00:03:47,140
Exhibit B: Baby Boy Hausen.

60
00:03:47,140 --> 00:03:49,380
Another term baby, 48 hours old.

61
00:03:50,090 --> 00:03:52,790
Brought into the NICU
three hours before the Hartig baby.

62
00:03:52,790 --> 00:03:55,860
Fever of unknown origin,
101 degrees, trending upwards.

63
00:03:56,600 --> 00:03:57,420
Wow, that is amazing.

64
00:03:57,420 --> 00:04:01,150
You hung out in the OB/GYN lounge all
morning and heard about two sick babies.

65
00:04:01,160 --> 00:04:03,040
- It's eerie.
- Don't touch that.

66
00:04:03,560 --> 00:04:04,420
Alright.

67
00:04:04,420 --> 00:04:06,720
We have an infection
spreading in the hospital.

68
00:04:08,180 --> 00:04:10,710
These kids have totally
unrelated illnesses.

69
00:04:10,720 --> 00:04:13,450
They fell sick within four hours
of each other.

70
00:04:13,450 --> 00:04:15,560
They had the same delivery
rooms, maternity rooms

71
00:04:15,560 --> 00:04:17,380
and neighboring, so
transmission's possible.

72
00:04:17,580 --> 00:04:20,450
- They have the same symptoms.
- The Hartig girl has a bowel obstruction.

73
00:04:20,460 --> 00:04:23,240
No matter how close their beds are, I'm
pretty sure kids can't share a blockage.

74
00:04:23,240 --> 00:04:25,740
What does bowel obstruction
on a chart indicate?

75
00:04:26,720 --> 00:04:29,850
Normally I'd say it indicates
a patient's bowel is obstructed,

76
00:04:29,860 --> 00:04:31,770
but I'm pretty sure you have
some deeper truth to impart.

77
00:04:31,780 --> 00:04:34,230
It means that some random
doctor of indeterminate

78
00:04:34,240 --> 00:04:36,570
skill thinks that the patient's
bowel is obstructed.

79
00:04:36,580 --> 00:04:38,870
Okay, you're upset because they
threw you out of their lounge.

80
00:04:38,880 --> 00:04:39,880
Look at the X-ray.

81
00:04:40,080 --> 00:04:41,250
It's a normal gas pattern.

82
00:04:41,260 --> 00:04:42,120
If you want, I can get you

83
00:04:42,120 --> 00:04:43,850
- ...a key to the oncology lounge.
- Air in the colon.

84
00:04:43,860 --> 00:04:45,210
- We're getting TiVo.
- If it's air,

85
00:04:45,220 --> 00:04:46,260
no bowel obstruction.

86
00:04:47,000 --> 00:04:49,570
Even if it is air, it could have
been there before the obstruction.

87
00:04:49,580 --> 00:04:53,980
No. Something's infected
both these infants.

88
00:04:55,720 --> 00:04:58,830
And you're the only one
who put this together because...

89
00:04:58,840 --> 00:05:01,220
Because I'm the only one
who looked at both kids.

90
00:05:01,220 --> 00:05:04,165
I want them isolated.
I want the maternity ward shut down.

91
00:05:04,165 --> 00:05:06,670
Because you're better at reading
an X-ray than a radiologist.

92
00:05:06,680 --> 00:05:09,110
Radiologists always
over-read babies' X-rays,

93
00:05:09,120 --> 00:05:11,110
especially if they're asked
to rule out a pathology.

94
00:05:11,120 --> 00:05:14,030
- He read into it what he wanted.
- Which is exactly what you're doing.

95
00:05:14,040 --> 00:05:17,790
You're finding a cluster because you
think it's interesting to find a cluster.

96
00:05:17,800 --> 00:05:21,090
Two plain old sick babies
would bore you.

97
00:05:21,100 --> 00:05:23,430
See, this is why I don't
waste money on shrinks,

98
00:05:23,440 --> 00:05:25,690
'cause you give me all these
really great insights for free.

99
00:05:25,700 --> 00:05:26,700
Shrink.

100
00:05:26,700 --> 00:05:30,500
If you would consider going to
a shrink, I would pay for it myself.

101
00:05:30,570 --> 00:05:33,390
The hospital would hold
a bake sale, for God's sake.

102
00:05:33,390 --> 00:05:35,238
We have an epidemic!

103
00:05:36,520 --> 00:05:41,680
Two sick babies is very sad,
but it doesn't prove an epidemic.

104
00:05:47,700 --> 00:05:49,085
How many do?

105
00:05:52,110 --> 00:05:54,420
Get up. We're going hunting.

106
00:05:55,210 --> 00:05:56,210
For what?

107
00:05:57,350 --> 00:05:58,350
Wabbits.

108
00:06:10,480 --> 00:06:12,400
Hi. Bye.

109
00:06:13,020 --> 00:06:14,360
He's screaming. He's fine.

110
00:06:20,240 --> 00:06:21,534
Good-looking baby.

111
00:06:25,980 --> 00:06:29,310
Oh, sorry. Wrong room.
We'll see you later.

112
00:06:29,720 --> 00:06:31,000
Twelve rooms, right? That's it?

113
00:06:31,650 --> 00:06:35,089
Yep. We've definitely
checked the whole floor.

114
00:06:36,490 --> 00:06:38,000
Good news. No epidemic.

115
00:06:39,230 --> 00:06:40,230
Tragic, huh?

116
00:06:43,980 --> 00:06:45,934
Overflow rooms, third floor.

117
00:06:46,480 --> 00:06:49,200
This imaginary infection
has spread to the next floor?

118
00:06:50,640 --> 00:06:54,234
- We were just gonna call.
- Did he get hot all of a sudden?

119
00:06:55,740 --> 00:06:56,740
Yeah.

120
00:07:01,580 --> 00:07:03,060
Yeah, I'll take care of that for you.

121
00:07:07,750 --> 00:07:10,600
Almost there, honey.
Don't worry. We're almost there.

122
00:07:11,790 --> 00:07:13,410
Excuse me! Hi.

123
00:07:13,420 --> 00:07:13,900
Hi.

124
00:07:13,900 --> 00:07:14,940
Intake sent you up here?

125
00:07:14,940 --> 00:07:16,060
Yeah, my wife's contractions...

126
00:07:16,060 --> 00:07:18,790
- ...are less than...
- Okay, Intake messed up. I am very, very sorry.

127
00:07:18,800 --> 00:07:21,790
Nurse Alpert will arrange
for an ambulance...

128
00:07:21,800 --> 00:07:24,820
to take you to Princeton General.

129
00:07:25,120 --> 00:07:27,070
The maternity ward is temporarily closed.

130
00:07:27,080 --> 00:07:28,420
We have to leave?

131
00:07:28,810 --> 00:07:31,340
- Yes. I am very sorry.
- Why are you doing this?

132
00:07:31,760 --> 00:07:34,691
You will be there
very, very soon.

133
00:07:36,480 --> 00:07:38,027
Happy now?

134
00:07:38,027 --> 00:07:39,390
No.

135
00:07:39,390 --> 00:07:41,155
But I am interested.

136
00:07:48,860 --> 00:07:52,870
Three sick babies, and a fourth
showing early symptoms.

137
00:07:53,080 --> 00:07:54,750
- How bad?
- Spiking fevers.

138
00:07:54,760 --> 00:07:57,470
B.P.'s plummeting.
They're barely able to keep systolic up.

139
00:07:57,480 --> 00:07:59,010
At this rate, they
could be dead in a day.

140
00:07:59,020 --> 00:08:00,000
Where did this come from?

141
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:02,040
Two delivery rooms, four
different maternity rooms.

142
00:08:02,040 --> 00:08:04,060
No common personnel and
no common equipment.

143
00:08:04,060 --> 00:08:05,940
- There's got to be something in common.
- Yeah.

144
00:08:06,540 --> 00:08:09,650
That would be the difference
between an epidemic and a coincidence.

145
00:08:09,660 --> 00:08:12,060
I'm putting a team together.
We're gonna start swabbing.

146
00:08:12,830 --> 00:08:17,030
What's she gonna swab? Every respirator,
sink, vent, drain in the entire hospital?

147
00:08:17,040 --> 00:08:18,830
- That'll take months.
- Needle in a haystack.

148
00:08:18,840 --> 00:08:21,710
It's worse than that, We don't even
know it's a needle we're looking for.

149
00:08:21,720 --> 00:08:22,810
Then why'd you let her go do it?

150
00:08:22,820 --> 00:08:26,440
Because the hospital is her
baby, and her baby's sick.

151
00:08:26,480 --> 00:08:28,360
If she doesn't solve this
soon, her head's gonna

152
00:08:28,360 --> 00:08:30,140
explode, and I don't
want to get any on me.

153
00:08:30,140 --> 00:08:31,950
So let's figure out
what's in the haystack.

154
00:08:31,960 --> 00:08:34,400
- Differential diagnosis, people.
- Parasite.

155
00:08:34,400 --> 00:08:36,550
- It's spreading too quickly.
- Next?

156
00:08:36,550 --> 00:08:37,360
Virus?

157
00:08:37,360 --> 00:08:40,560
The kids are too sick, and the
blood tests showed no lymphocytosis.

158
00:08:40,930 --> 00:08:43,490
And they're not responding
to acyclovir or ribavirin.

159
00:08:43,490 --> 00:08:46,090
If it's some other virus,
we'll never find it in time anyway.

160
00:08:46,100 --> 00:08:49,860
Which leads us
to bacterial infection.

161
00:08:49,870 --> 00:08:53,630
It's not responding to broad-spectrum
antibiotics, so we've got something resistant.

162
00:08:53,640 --> 00:08:57,130
- The usual suspects?
- MRSA. It's always MRSA in hospitals.

163
00:08:57,560 --> 00:09:00,150
Maybe contaminated food
or water source.

164
00:09:00,160 --> 00:09:01,160
Pseudomonas.

165
00:09:01,720 --> 00:09:03,810
- V.R.E.?
- "H" flu.

166
00:09:04,800 --> 00:09:06,970
Okay. Those are the big ones.

167
00:09:06,980 --> 00:09:10,140
Cultures will take 48 hours.
Might as well be postmortem.

168
00:09:10,860 --> 00:09:15,640
We'll start them on vancomycin for the
MRSA and aztreonam to cover the rest.

169
00:09:15,840 --> 00:09:19,500
Let's get M.R.I.'s, check for
abscesses or some occult infection.

170
00:09:20,070 --> 00:09:23,560
I'll be in the clinic. Grab me if you find
something important, or unimportant.

171
00:10:25,730 --> 00:10:30,810
We did an M.R.I. on all the babies, and,
unfortunately, we didn't find anything,

172
00:10:31,180 --> 00:10:34,287
so we're starting them on the
strongest antibiotics that we've got,

173
00:10:34,940 --> 00:10:37,248
and we're hoping that
that will take care of it.

174
00:10:38,050 --> 00:10:39,417
But he's so tiny.

175
00:10:40,180 --> 00:10:41,544
How sick is he?

176
00:10:42,380 --> 00:10:45,760
His fever's up to 103.5,
and his blood pressure is 80 over 40.

177
00:10:46,060 --> 00:10:48,342
How, um...
How bad is that?

178
00:10:52,130 --> 00:10:55,960
It's low. The heart needs
to circulate the blood.

179
00:10:56,030 --> 00:10:59,840
If it's weak, the oxygen isn't getting
to the liver, the kidneys, the brain.

180
00:11:02,100 --> 00:11:03,670
I have to ask you something.

181
00:11:03,740 --> 00:11:05,580
- Judy...
- No, no, Kim. Let me.

182
00:11:08,140 --> 00:11:11,000
I had a cold last month,
and I told the doctors about it.

183
00:11:11,220 --> 00:11:12,910
Honey, this has nothing
to do with you.

184
00:11:13,340 --> 00:11:14,340
Kim's right.

185
00:11:15,420 --> 00:11:16,900
Your son was born healthy.

186
00:11:17,160 --> 00:11:19,248
He caught the infection
after his birth.

187
00:11:21,160 --> 00:11:23,250
There's no reason to think
that he caught it from you.

188
00:11:23,280 --> 00:11:27,430
But you don't know. I mean,
you don't know how he got sick.

189
00:11:33,020 --> 00:11:35,900
Pretty standard question...
"How sick is my child?"

190
00:11:35,900 --> 00:11:37,600
- You couldn't answer.
- I answered.

191
00:11:37,600 --> 00:11:40,210
You rattled off numbers...
B.P., O2 sats.

192
00:11:40,340 --> 00:11:41,960
- It's not what they need to know.
- What they need

193
00:11:41,960 --> 00:11:44,040
to know is the future.
You got a Magic 8 ball?

194
00:11:44,810 --> 00:11:46,740
No, just eight years
of medical training.

195
00:11:50,360 --> 00:11:54,570
Look, I realize it's tough
to break bad news to families.

196
00:11:54,580 --> 00:11:55,740
Not as tough as hearing it.

197
00:11:56,600 --> 00:11:59,440
And I guess being the poor guy dying
is the toughest of all?

198
00:12:00,960 --> 00:12:01,960
No.

199
00:12:03,460 --> 00:12:05,900
It's easier to die
than to watch someone die.

200
00:12:11,340 --> 00:12:14,345
Well, we're checking the vents.
It could be airborne.

201
00:12:15,010 --> 00:12:17,920
Somebody get the sinks, too,
and underneath them.

202
00:12:17,920 --> 00:12:18,920
I'll get it.

203
00:12:19,560 --> 00:12:22,740
How many med students
have you got swabbing the decks?

204
00:12:23,220 --> 00:12:25,940
What else are they gonna do?
It's not like they're delivering babies.

205
00:12:26,180 --> 00:12:28,740
- You find anything yet?
- Uh, yeah.

206
00:12:28,750 --> 00:12:32,540
About half the antibacterial gel
dispensers are empty or broken.

207
00:12:32,550 --> 00:12:35,783
That's bad, yet diagnostically
completely insignificant.

208
00:12:36,360 --> 00:12:41,490
Well, if the staff can't wash their hands,
it's no wonder an infection has spread.

209
00:12:41,490 --> 00:12:44,570
- Hey! Tie clip!
- Sorry?

210
00:12:44,570 --> 00:12:48,629
We have an epidemic in this hospital,
and your tie is becoming a petri dish.

211
00:12:49,240 --> 00:12:51,465
Put on a tie clip
or take the damn thing off.

212
00:12:54,650 --> 00:12:58,889
My joints have been feeling all loose,
and lately I've been feeling sick a lot.

213
00:12:59,250 --> 00:13:00,770
Maybe I'm over-training.

214
00:13:00,780 --> 00:13:05,160
I'm doing the marathon, like, 10 miles a
day, but I can't seem to lose any weight.

215
00:13:05,440 --> 00:13:06,440
Lift up your arms.

216
00:13:10,360 --> 00:13:11,760
You have a parasite.

217
00:13:13,170 --> 00:13:15,880
- Like a tapeworm or something?
- Lie back and lift up your sweater.

218
00:13:17,860 --> 00:13:19,285
You can put your arms down.

219
00:13:20,320 --> 00:13:23,410
- Can you do anything about it?
- Only for about a month or so.

220
00:13:23,410 --> 00:13:26,530
After that it becomes illegal to remove,
except in a couple states.

221
00:13:26,540 --> 00:13:28,800
- Illegal?
- But don't worry.

222
00:13:29,460 --> 00:13:31,881
Many women learn
to embrace this parasite.

223
00:13:32,140 --> 00:13:36,520
They name it, dress it up in tiny clothes,
arrange play dates with other parasites.

224
00:13:36,590 --> 00:13:39,680
- Play dates?
- It has your eyes.

225
00:13:42,430 --> 00:13:44,550
But that's impossible.

226
00:13:44,560 --> 00:13:47,480
Well, I assume you weren't
getting your period.

227
00:13:47,840 --> 00:13:49,560
Maybe that should have
given you an inkling.

228
00:13:50,100 --> 00:13:52,350
- But I'm on this birth control implant.
- Yeah, I know.

229
00:13:52,360 --> 00:13:54,920
- I saw the scar on your arm.
- And my doctor said I

230
00:13:54,920 --> 00:13:57,570
might not get any periods
at all if it was working.

231
00:13:57,810 --> 00:14:01,450
Interestingly enough, you also
don't get any periods if it isn't working,

232
00:14:01,460 --> 00:14:04,400
which is why you were supposed
to get regular pregnancy tests.

233
00:14:04,400 --> 00:14:06,940
I'm gonna send a nurse in here
to schedule your prenatal care.

234
00:14:06,940 --> 00:14:10,086
You're due in about five months,
so start planning the shower.

235
00:14:12,338 --> 00:14:13,530
Doctor?

236
00:14:13,820 --> 00:14:18,320
Please, me and my husband
wanted to have a kid soon,

237
00:14:19,200 --> 00:14:20,680
but, oh, God,

238
00:14:21,700 --> 00:14:25,680
like four months ago,
we had this really big fight.

