they're probably all checked out by now.

479
00:30:51,810 --> 00:30:54,540
No, the Limpert boy had a bit of jaundice.
He's checking out today.

480
00:30:54,540 --> 00:30:56,310
- I want to test his blood too.
- Why?

481
00:30:56,380 --> 00:30:58,460
Because we need
all the information we can get.

482
00:30:58,710 --> 00:31:00,370
The healthy kid
can be our control group.

483
00:31:00,370 --> 00:31:04,170
I'll just tell his parents he can't
check out because he has the smallpox.

484
00:31:07,540 --> 00:31:10,520
<i>Stephen Morgan,
contact Hospital Administration.</i>

485
00:31:14,400 --> 00:31:16,360
<i>Dr. Paul to the Recovery Room.</i>

486
00:31:19,200 --> 00:31:22,117
All done. All done.

487
00:31:25,900 --> 00:31:26,900
What did we get?

488
00:31:27,110 --> 00:31:30,166
Well, the sick babies
all tested positive for echovirus 11.

489
00:31:30,166 --> 00:31:33,510
- Great.
- And C.M.V., and parvovirus B-19.

490
00:31:33,510 --> 00:31:34,690
Three viruses?

491
00:31:34,900 --> 00:31:36,840
But what's weirder, the
healthy kid we tested,

492
00:31:36,840 --> 00:31:39,960
he's positive for echovirus 11
and C.M.V. antibodies as well.

493
00:31:45,830 --> 00:31:47,520
They're infants.

494
00:31:49,030 --> 00:31:51,720
They have their mother's blood,
their mother's antibodies.

495
00:31:52,670 --> 00:31:54,020
So we've just learned nothing?

496
00:31:54,460 --> 00:31:56,670
We have half the picture.
The healthy kids survived

497
00:31:56,680 --> 00:31:58,820
because their mothers'
antibodies saved them.

498
00:31:58,820 --> 00:32:01,080
If the mom had C.M.V. in
the past, she'd have the

499
00:32:01,080 --> 00:32:03,320
antibodies for C.M.V. The kid
would be immune from it.

500
00:32:04,810 --> 00:32:09,140
So, we test the sick kids' moms
for echovirus, C.M.V. and parvovirus.

501
00:32:09,140 --> 00:32:11,020
And whichever they
don't have the antibodies for,

502
00:32:11,020 --> 00:32:12,751
that's what's killing their kids.

503
00:32:13,520 --> 00:32:14,794
I'll test the mothers.

504
00:32:34,560 --> 00:32:39,470
<i>Dr. Kent's office, one.</i>

505
00:32:59,070 --> 00:33:00,340
Echovirus 11.

506
00:33:00,820 --> 00:33:03,770
It's an enterovirus.
It lodges in the intestinal tract.

507
00:33:03,840 --> 00:33:08,360
Enteroviruses cause diarrhea and flu-like
symptoms in adults, maybe a rash,

508
00:33:08,780 --> 00:33:11,440
but for newborns,
it can be deadly.

509
00:33:12,210 --> 00:33:14,020
It's damaging her heart.

510
00:33:15,040 --> 00:33:16,981
Well, is there anything
you can do?

511
00:33:16,981 --> 00:33:19,960
Viruses are more difficult to treat
than bacterial infections.

512
00:33:20,640 --> 00:33:22,560
We still haven't found a cure
for the common cold.

513
00:33:22,590 --> 00:33:24,990
So, you mean there's no vaccine or...

514
00:33:24,990 --> 00:33:27,700
There's a company in Pennsylvania
developing an antiviral.

515
00:33:27,700 --> 00:33:29,920
It got positive results
in a lab setting.

516
00:33:30,280 --> 00:33:31,871
We managed
to get our hands on it.

517
00:33:45,320 --> 00:33:47,460
Imagine not being able
to touch your own baby.

518
00:33:51,720 --> 00:33:53,840
- Can I get your guys' help
with something?
- Sure.

519
00:33:54,660 --> 00:33:56,771
- Your daughter, her...
- Maxine.

520
00:33:57,530 --> 00:34:00,480
That's her name... Maxine.

521
00:34:02,340 --> 00:34:06,120
We need someone to hold Maxine up off the
bed while the nurse changes her sheet.

522
00:34:06,430 --> 00:34:08,283
Sure. Okay.

523
00:34:10,900 --> 00:34:13,680
Look at you. Hi.

524
00:34:14,600 --> 00:34:15,760
Hold still.

525
00:34:21,280 --> 00:34:22,280
That's it.

526
00:34:26,850 --> 00:34:30,800
Hi. Easy. Shh.

527
00:34:31,260 --> 00:34:32,260
There you go.

528
00:35:07,900 --> 00:35:08,900
Hey, Foreman.

529
00:35:09,950 --> 00:35:10,950
Got a minute?

530
00:35:18,280 --> 00:35:22,780
So, pulmonary resistance has stabilized
for the two kids, but, uh, B.P.'s still...

531
00:35:22,790 --> 00:35:25,100
No news then. How's Cameron?

532
00:35:26,220 --> 00:35:28,560
- Dr. Cameron?
- Sure.

533
00:35:29,020 --> 00:35:32,280
Let's start with her and then move on
to all the other Camerons we know.

534
00:35:32,500 --> 00:35:35,960
I'm sorry. I'm just not used to you
asking about someone's well-being.

535
00:35:35,970 --> 00:35:38,290
I can understand how the
question would surprise you.

536
00:35:38,300 --> 00:35:40,160
I don't quite get how it
would confuse you.

537
00:35:40,840 --> 00:35:43,560
- Why do you wanna know?
- Why do you wanna know why I want to know?

538
00:35:44,000 --> 00:35:46,280
- Just curious.
- Me too.

539
00:35:46,700 --> 00:35:47,820
You don't get curious.

540
00:35:48,700 --> 00:35:51,570
I'm the most curious man in the world.
Not about trivialities.

541
00:35:51,580 --> 00:35:53,680
Well, then
this must not be trivial.

542
00:35:55,700 --> 00:35:57,440
How is Cameron
handling everything?

543
00:35:58,710 --> 00:35:59,710
Just fine.

544
00:36:03,020 --> 00:36:05,274
Great. Glad we talked.

545
00:36:11,090 --> 00:36:14,826
Your husband is definitely
the source of your mono.

546
00:36:15,060 --> 00:36:17,495
Oh. Wow!

547
00:36:17,700 --> 00:36:19,163
Oh, thank God.

548
00:36:20,030 --> 00:36:22,520
Wow. I'm gonna be a mom.

549
00:36:22,940 --> 00:36:24,335
Whoa!

550
00:36:25,040 --> 00:36:28,900
Thank you so much. I gotta
get you a gift or something.

551
00:36:28,910 --> 00:36:32,100
Sometimes the best gift
is the gift of never seeing you again.

552
00:36:32,100 --> 00:36:33,880
Okay. Alright.

553
00:36:34,350 --> 00:36:38,050
But, Dr. House,
you've been so awesome.

554
00:36:38,050 --> 00:36:42,160
I mean,
I really totally trust you.

555
00:36:42,560 --> 00:36:44,180
- Do you think you...
- No.

556
00:36:44,700 --> 00:36:46,390
Could do the prenatal...

557
00:36:46,390 --> 00:36:46,890
No.

558
00:36:46,890 --> 00:36:49,450
- Or deliver the baby?
- That would be "no".

559
00:36:49,450 --> 00:36:50,530
Okay.

560
00:36:57,040 --> 00:36:58,040
Wow.

561
00:37:35,740 --> 00:37:37,140
Chase, take a look at this.

562
00:37:55,760 --> 00:37:58,860
Oh, God. It's good news.

563
00:37:59,240 --> 00:38:00,540
No. It's great.

564
00:38:05,060 --> 00:38:06,920
Thank you.

565
00:38:18,860 --> 00:38:20,880
- Hi.
- She's doing great.

566
00:38:20,880 --> 00:38:22,500
Hi, little girl.

567
00:38:36,740 --> 00:38:39,637
- They all gone?
- Hartigs are checking out right now.

568
00:38:41,480 --> 00:38:43,810
- You look tired.
- Thanks.

569
00:38:45,280 --> 00:38:48,880
It's no wonder. You've had a hard
time the last couple of days.

570
00:38:49,980 --> 00:38:51,274
And you haven't?

571
00:38:52,090 --> 00:38:53,317
Not like you.

572
00:38:56,620 --> 00:38:58,156
Anyone who's that awkward...

573
00:38:59,360 --> 00:39:02,600
either has no experience
with death or too much,

574
00:39:03,600 --> 00:39:05,329
and I'm pretty sure
it's not the former.

575
00:39:07,870 --> 00:39:10,720
Chase told me about that idea you had,
the parents holding the baby.

576
00:39:11,310 --> 00:39:12,310
Where'd you get that?

577
00:39:16,180 --> 00:39:17,240
Did you lose someone?

578
00:39:20,110 --> 00:39:21,440
Did you lose a baby?

579
00:39:24,820 --> 00:39:26,434
You can be a real bastard.

580
00:40:29,750 --> 00:40:30,998
Unfinished business?

581
00:40:32,833 --> 00:40:34,320
I'm in the haystack.

582
00:40:34,320 --> 00:40:37,090
Ah, because now you know
you're looking for a needle.

583
00:40:37,090 --> 00:40:38,090
Right.

584
00:40:38,580 --> 00:40:42,220
If I tell you to let it go,
it won't make any difference, will it?

585
00:40:43,100 --> 00:40:45,770
Enteroviruses
are spread by humans.

586
00:40:45,770 --> 00:40:47,200
Fecal oral usually.

587
00:40:47,670 --> 00:40:49,310
It could be respiratory
secretions though.

588
00:40:50,340 --> 00:40:53,230
So Cuddy got stool samples from the whole
staff. Just wait till they come back.

589
00:40:53,240 --> 00:40:54,939
- That won't do it.
- Why not?

590
00:40:55,160 --> 00:40:57,010
The shedder, whoever he is,

591
00:40:57,220 --> 00:40:59,750
he's so virulent,
he must have been symptomatic.

592
00:40:59,750 --> 00:41:01,320
Cuddy would have noticed him.

593
00:41:02,180 --> 00:41:04,740
And the babies didn't share
any common personnel.

594
00:41:05,650 --> 00:41:09,420
- That's what's weird.
- Yeah, yeah. That's what's weird.

595
00:41:09,720 --> 00:41:11,372
<i>Transition Team to O.R. 2.</i>

596
00:41:11,760 --> 00:41:13,880
<i>Transition Team to O.R. 2.</i>

597
00:42:06,780 --> 00:42:08,137
Can I help you?

598
00:42:12,700 --> 00:42:15,940
- You saved my life.
- I just ran some tests.

599
00:42:16,760 --> 00:42:19,100
Your will and determination
are what saved your life.

600
00:42:19,520 --> 00:42:22,440
- I know who I am now.
- Yes, you do.

601
00:42:23,240 --> 00:42:24,690
<i>And I know who I am as well.</i>

602
00:42:25,071 --> 00:42:26,360
<i>Naomi, I love you.</i>

